{"text":"Justin, you are absolutely correct, your spidey sense should have been tingling.  We don't have the mechanisms in place to directly compute that right now.  However, once we get to quaternions, we will directly compute this.  I just posted the video a few hours ago if you're chomping at the bit and wanted to get to this early."}

{"text":"Hi Brent, good to hear from you again.  I just went out and measured and I think you'll be OK.  The distance between the front face of the ladder and the car side is a little over 9\".  However, I assume you'd mount the tank on the side of the ladder (so it wouldn't interfere with your feet as you ascended/descended the ladder).  In that case, the limiting dimension is really the distance between the face of the door and the side of the vehicle which is more like 18\".  I also don't have my ladder positioned to maximize the clearance.  If you re-position the ladder you could probably squeeze another inch or two of clearance.  Thanks for watching!"}

{"text":"Hi Brent, yes, I'm planning on getting that video up in the future.  I've got a playlist of all my van videos at "},{"text":"https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLxdnSsBqCrrF5nO7cmNTc4cct0miFWdO6","playlistLink":{"externalPlaylistId":"PLxdnSsBqCrrF5nO7cmNTc4cct0miFWdO6"}},{"text":".  If you subscribe to the channel, hopefully you'll get notified when that video goes up.  In short, I didn't have to add any extra support other than a rod to mount the equipment.  The tray is bolted into the roof fairly securely.  Thanks for watching!"}
{"text":"Thanks for watching.  Yes, I do have plans for a video on masking but it might take me a while to get to it as I have a few others in front.  I'll let you know once it gets posted."}
{"text":"I'm glad they are helpful, thanks for watching and I hope to catch you at a future video!"}

{"text":"Actually I did figure it out.  I don't think it is a problem with being retracted too far, rather it is a problem if the housing is tipped too far away from the normal, vertical position.  I believe there is a mechanical system in place that engages if you are in an accident and the van has rolled over onto its side.  This system engages and prevents the seat belts from extending.  To fix this, just place the housings in their normal position and then start rattling the seat belt and it should pop loose and extend again.  Let me know of this works for you."}
